of class, I'm not promising...

241
00:21:13,386 --> 00:21:16,106
...because I want us to get
to our breathing exercises...

242
00:21:16,307 --> 00:21:20,859
...but if we have time, we might try
a spiky arrangement or two.

243
00:21:21,068 --> 00:21:25,824
But first we're gonna start by doing
a little work treating our stems.

244
00:21:26,029 --> 00:21:29,739
And we're gonna start by working
with our woody stems...

245
00:21:29,950 --> 00:21:35,503
...because they can be a little on the
tricky side and require the most TLC.

246
00:21:35,711 --> 00:21:37,429
Tough loving care.

247
00:21:38,311 --> 00:21:42,385
Okay, let's start with an azalea,
one of my favorites.

248
00:21:42,792 --> 00:21:46,229
Starting an inch or two
from the bottom of the stem...

249
00:21:46,433 --> 00:21:49,153
...and if it's a thick stem,
we really have to smash them...

250
00:21:49,354 --> 00:21:52,391
...we split the stem vertically.

251
00:21:52,594 --> 00:21:55,712
Does anyone know why we do this?

252
00:21:56,235 --> 00:21:59,911
Anyone? Yes.

253
00:22:00,356 --> 00:22:03,315
- So it will draw more water?
- Very good.

254
00:22:03,517 --> 00:22:07,510
Did everyone hear that?
So it will draw more water.

255
00:22:07,718 --> 00:22:12,873
Okay. Does everyone have
their hammers? Let's begin.

256
00:22:29,562 --> 00:22:31,041
You're supposed to be in bed.

257
00:22:31,242 --> 00:22:33,393
I needed to get some turkey franks
and milk for Julio.

258
00:22:33,603 --> 00:22:36,357
Why didn't you call me? I could've
stopped home on my way from work.

259
00:22:36,564 --> 00:22:39,158
- He has a snack at 3:30.
- Why didn't you call your sister?

260
00:22:40,364 --> 00:22:42,799
She just got two days
on a new Nicolas Cage movie.

261
00:22:43,005 --> 00:22:45,759
She plays this hooker who witnesses
a murder, then gets raped and killed.

262
00:22:45,966 --> 00:22:49,276
She's got lines and everything! She
wants me to come visit her on the set.

263
00:22:49,486 --> 00:22:50,556
Well, you're supposed to be in bed.

264
00:22:50,767 --> 00:22:53,327
I got bored and went to the market.
What's the big deal?

265
00:22:53,527 --> 00:22:56,122
- What are you doing home anyway?
- I came home for lunch.

266
00:22:56,328 --> 00:22:59,604
- I was worried.
- Rico, please. I'm fine.

267
00:22:59,808 --> 00:23:01,640
I'm not just worried about you.

268
00:23:04,009 --> 00:23:07,525
Okay.
This is about the baby at work.

269
00:23:08,130 --> 00:23:10,520
I just...
I can't do it.

270
00:23:11,091 --> 00:23:14,049
Of course you can.

271
00:23:18,212 --> 00:23:20,204
He looks like...

272
00:23:20,413 --> 00:23:22,449
Like he's sleeping.

273
00:23:22,653 --> 00:23:25,851
Like a baby who's fallen asleep.

274
00:23:26,054 --> 00:23:31,687
He was 3 weeks old.
There was nothing wrong with him.

275
00:23:32,095 --> 00:23:35,372
And then, just like that...

276
00:23:35,576 --> 00:23:37,771
...he dies.

277
00:23:38,417 --> 00:23:40,885
For no reason.

278
00:23:41,617 --> 00:23:43,290
How can that be?

279
00:23:43,498 --> 00:23:48,175
How can the beginning and end
be so damn close together?

280
00:23:50,419 --> 00:23:54,333
And now I've got this real bad feeling.

281
00:23:55,860 --> 00:23:59,171
I haven't done a baby
since Julio was born.

282
00:23:59,381 --> 00:24:01,770
David always does them.

283
00:24:03,862 --> 00:24:09,460
- So make David do this one.
- David's in Vegas until tomorrow.

284
00:24:09,663 --> 00:24:12,542
The viewing is this afternoon.

285
00:24:16,985 --> 00:24:21,298
Some babies just aren't meant
for this world, Rico.

286
00:24:22,866 --> 00:24:25,426
But this one is.

287
00:24:36,189 --> 00:24:37,986
Turn to page seven
in your notebooks...

288
00:24:38,189 --> 00:24:40,465
...we'll go step by step
through the most challenging...

289
00:24:40,670 --> 00:24:45,108
...cranial facial reconstruction
I ever faced.

290
00:24:45,311 --> 00:24:47,779
If we could go to
the next slide, please.

291
00:24:50,992 --> 00:24:53,984
- Oh, my God.
- Oh, Jesus.

292
00:24:54,713 --> 00:24:59,230
- That shit is fucked up.
- Nate, this is Chloe Yorkin.

293
00:24:59,434 --> 00:25:02,506
The job Federico left us
to do for Kroehner?

294
00:25:02,714 --> 00:25:04,990
Oh, God.
That is like fucking science fiction.

295
00:25:06,955 --> 00:25:10,107
The first question my team
and I asked ourselves was not...

296
00:25:10,316 --> 00:25:13,114
...as it might have been at a
facility with less resources...

297
00:25:13,316 --> 00:25:17,151
...can we do this?
- They don't even credit Rico by name.

298
00:25:17,357 --> 00:25:20,430
Oh, man, he's gonna be furious.

299
00:25:25,799 --> 00:25:27,596
Oh, God.

300
00:25:27,800 --> 00:25:29,950
Well, that is a very generous
offer, Roger...

301
00:25:30,160 --> 00:25:33,995
...but unfortunately I am in a relationship
at the moment. If I was...

302
00:25:34,201 --> 00:25:36,396
Deal me in.

303
00:25:38,082 --> 00:25:40,471
Jesus, Billy.

304
00:25:40,682 --> 00:25:43,720
Hold on. Hey!
So where's your boyfriend?

305
00:25:43,923 --> 00:25:46,357
What are you doing here?

306
00:25:46,603 --> 00:25:48,322
I love Vegas.
You know I love Vegas.

307
00:25:48,524 --> 00:25:52,040
And sometimes when my sister isn't
there when I need her, I hop in my car...

308
00:25:52,245 --> 00:25:54,634
...start driving, wind up here.
- Billy, you're lying.

309
00:25:54,845 --> 00:25:57,314
I'm really not.
I just saw you at the blackjack table.

310
00:25:57,526 --> 00:25:59,596
- It was a total coincidence.
- You're a fucking liar.

311
00:25:59,806 --> 00:26:03,356
You're a selfish, manipulative,
narcissistic liar.

312
00:26:06,648 --> 00:26:11,484
- What did Mom and Dad tell you?
- They told me that you made a bomb.

313
00:26:13,529 --> 00:26:17,318
That's fucking hilarious.
So now I'm like, what, a terrorist?

314
00:26:17,530 --> 00:26:19,646
"Billy Mc Veigh"?

315
00:26:21,811 --> 00:26:23,722
They're fucking liars, Brenda!

316
00:26:23,931 --> 00:26:26,890
They hate each other and they're
miserable and they're jealous of us...

317
00:26:27,092 --> 00:26:29,367
...and they want us to hate
each other too. So they lie to us!

318
00:26:29,572 --> 00:26:32,804
No, they lied to me, you lied to me. You
let me believe you tried to kill yourself.

319
00:26:33,013 --> 00:26:34,162
Do you know how fucked that is?

320
00:26:34,373 --> 00:26:36,683
You know what?
I was so fucking drugged up...

321
00:26:36,894 --> 00:26:38,612
...I don't even really
remember what happened.

322
00:26:38,814 --> 00:26:40,692
Dad showed me what you wrote.

323
00:26:45,936 --> 00:26:48,052
I was kidding, okay?

324
00:26:48,817 --> 00:26:51,456
It wasn't serious.

325
00:26:52,057 --> 00:26:56,176
Do you have any idea
what I gave up for you?

326
00:26:56,378 --> 00:26:59,496
Because I thought that if you tried
to kill yourself again and succeeded...

327
00:26:59,699 --> 00:27:02,657
...I could tell myself that I did
everything I could to save you.

328
00:27:02,859 --> 00:27:04,293
And you did.

329
00:27:05,180 --> 00:27:08,412
- You've saved me every day since then.
- Well, fuck you!

330
00:27:08,621 --> 00:27:11,658
- Brenda, don't fucking walk away...
- I'm having a life. Just back off!

331
00:27:11,861 --> 00:27:14,137
Hey, you heard her! Now, fuck off!

332
00:27:19,303 --> 00:27:21,419
Nice.

333
00:27:26,865 --> 00:27:28,981
Are you okay?

334
00:27:29,745 --> 00:27:32,385
He followed us here.

335
00:27:34,066 --> 00:27:38,060
I hate to say it,
but I'm not entirely surprised.

336
00:28:15,435 --> 00:28:17,903
Very nice.

337
00:28:18,515 --> 00:28:20,905
Luscious.

338
00:28:24,197 --> 00:28:25,789
This is a little...

339
00:28:25,997 --> 00:28:27,350
...tight.

340
00:28:27,557 --> 00:28:31,107
- Tight?
- You're not breathing right.

341
00:28:31,318 --> 00:28:34,072
- I'm not?
- You're breathing from here...

342
00:28:34,279 --> 00:28:36,873
...when you should be
breathing from here.

343
00:28:37,079 --> 00:28:39,116
- But my lungs are here.
- Of course they are.

344
00:28:39,320 --> 00:28:41,197
I'm speaking metaphorically.

345
00:28:41,400 --> 00:28:44,757
If you breathe from up here, your
arrangements will come from up here.

346
00:28:44,961 --> 00:28:49,592
If you breathe from down here, your
arrangements will come from down here.

347
00:28:49,802 --> 00:28:52,362
- And that's good?
- That's very good.

348
00:28:52,562 --> 00:28:54,315
- Do you do yoga?
- No.

349
00:28:54,523 --> 00:28:57,755
Okay. Would everybody grab
a yoga mat in the next room?

350
00:28:57,964 --> 00:29:02,641
We're gonna do some breathing
exercises before we break for dinner.

351
00:29:04,365 --> 00:29:06,754
You're a bit of a control freak,
aren't you?

352
00:29:06,966 --> 00:29:09,799
No, I'm not. I don't think I am.

353
00:29:10,006 --> 00:29:11,325
- Am I?
- Yes.

354
00:29:11,526 --> 00:29:14,360
And control freaks
do not make good arrangers.

355
00:29:14,567 --> 00:29:17,287
Believe me, I know.
I used to be a control freak too.

356
00:29:17,728 --> 00:29:20,196
But you know what?
You can get over it.

357
00:29:20,408 --> 00:29:23,162
All you have to do is learn to breathe.

358
00:29:23,569 --> 00:29:26,004
- Are you on antidepressants?
- No!

359
00:29:26,210 --> 00:29:29,759
Well, Lord knows I'd be lost
without my Saint John's Wort.

360
00:29:33,211 --> 00:29:37,251
There are countless challenges facing
independent funeral homes today:

361
00:29:37,452 --> 00:29:41,332
Changing social attitudes
toward death and dying...

362
00:29:41,533 --> 00:29:46,324
...economic hardship in communities
both large and small...

363
00:30:02,697 --> 00:30:05,166
Oh, what the hell.

364
00:30:06,698 --> 00:30:10,248
We all know what the real challenge is.

365
00:30:12,779 --> 00:30:15,658
How are you doing today, Mr. Gilardi?

366
00:30:16,260 --> 00:30:19,412
- Fine, thank you.
- Glad to hear it.

367
00:30:20,181 --> 00:30:22,695
We all know of a certain organization...

368
00:30:22,901 --> 00:30:25,939
...that controls the flow
of prep-room supplies...

369
00:30:26,142 --> 00:30:31,854
...caskets, cemetery property and
flowers to everyone in this room.

370
00:30:32,063 --> 00:30:34,624
And believe me, that organization
will stoop to almost any means...

371
00:30:34,824 --> 00:30:37,292
...to make sure that the independent
funeral home has no future.

372
00:30:37,505 --> 00:30:38,858
But hear me out.

373
00:30:40,665 --> 00:30:44,056
My father was in this business
for over 35 years.

374
00:30:44,266 --> 00:30:45,904
He...

375
00:30:46,706 --> 00:30:50,416
He thought it was okay to tell people
about a cheaper casket.

376
00:30:50,627 --> 00:30:53,620
He didn't always try
to talk people out of cremation.

377
00:30:53,828 --> 00:30:56,023
There were even times
where I actually heard him say:

378
00:30:56,228 --> 00:30:58,538
"To hell with our profit margin on this. "

379
00:30:59,389 --> 00:31:01,950
These words are heresy
to a certain organization...

380
00:31:02,150 --> 00:31:03,742
...because profit is all it cares about...

381
00:31:03,950 --> 00:31:07,626
...no matter how many PR-motivated
seminars it sponsors.

382
00:31:07,831 --> 00:31:09,981
That organization wants us
independents to believe...

383
00:31:10,191 --> 00:31:12,581
...that we cannot afford to be
like my father anymore.

384
00:31:12,792 --> 00:31:14,510
Well, I'm sorry, but that's bullshit.

385
00:31:14,712 --> 00:31:17,546
Don't get me wrong, my father
worried about the bottom line too...

386
00:31:17,753 --> 00:31:20,221
...but he worried more
about other things.

387
00:31:20,434 --> 00:31:22,345
Like comforting people...

388
00:31:22,554 --> 00:31:24,909
...and helping them face profound loss.

389
00:31:27,795 --> 00:31:33,154
Maybe now more than ever, we should
all try to be a little more like him.

390
00:31:35,117 --> 00:31:36,596
Thank you.

391
00:32:03,603 --> 00:32:06,163
- Very motivational.
- Good job.

392
00:32:07,363 --> 00:32:08,797
How'd I do?

393
00:32:09,004 --> 00:32:13,044
Are you kidding? You kicked
some serious ass, you big freak.

394
00:32:18,566 --> 00:32:21,603
You didn't come home last night.

395
00:32:22,607 --> 00:32:25,599
Well, it's not like it was a school night.

396
00:32:26,407 --> 00:32:29,286
Would you like me to
make you something to eat?

397
00:32:29,488 --> 00:32:31,923
Yeah, that'd be great.

398
00:32:38,730 --> 00:32:41,768
Do you think I'm a control freak?

399
00:32:42,971 --> 00:32:45,121
Yeah.

400
00:32:46,212 --> 00:32:50,968
- Where do you think David gets it from?
- Your father was very controlling.

401
00:32:51,173 --> 00:32:53,971
- Not like you.
- That's not nice.

402
00:32:54,453 --> 00:32:55,442
You asked.

403
00:32:59,454 --> 00:33:02,492
You're not as bad as you used to be.

404
00:33:03,455 --> 00:33:06,573
May I ask where you were all night?

405
00:33:07,536 --> 00:33:09,811
In Barstow.

406
00:33:10,017 --> 00:33:12,133
What in God's name
were you doing there?

407
00:33:12,337 --> 00:33:14,407
I was visiting a friend of mine
who's in the hospital.

408
00:33:14,617 --> 00:33:16,449
Who?

409
00:33:17,018 --> 00:33:19,486
Gabriel Dimas.

410
00:33:20,419 --> 00:33:24,413
- The young man whose brother...
- Yeah.

411
00:33:26,540 --> 00:33:29,294
What was he doing in the hospital?

412
00:33:30,461 --> 00:33:31,780
He OD'd.

413
00:33:32,901 --> 00:33:35,541
Good Lord.

414
00:33:37,382 --> 00:33:39,499
Claire...

415
00:33:40,343 --> 00:33:43,859
...he's obviously a deeply disturbed boy.

416
00:33:44,064 --> 00:33:48,616
You need to steer clear of him.
Let his family deal with this.

417
00:33:48,825 --> 00:33:52,738
Well, let's take stock
for a second, shall we?

418
00:33:54,066 --> 00:33:56,705
His little brother's dead.
His father's dead.

419
00:33:57,026 --> 00:33:58,858
His stepfather beat him up...

420
00:33:59,067 --> 00:34:02,947
...his white-trash mother who smokes
like a fish could give a shit.

421
00:34:03,148 --> 00:34:05,787
That leaves no one.

422
00:34:06,788 --> 00:34:10,099
Was his overdose an accident?

423
00:34:10,309 --> 00:34:13,825
- Of course it was an accident.
- Because sometimes these things aren't.

424
00:34:14,030 --> 00:34:18,104
And if it wasn't, it could happen again.
There's an 80%/% chance that someone...

425
00:34:18,311 --> 00:34:20,950
It wasn't a suicide attempt.

426
00:34:21,151 --> 00:34:23,302
I hope, for his sake, you're right.

427
00:34:24,312 --> 00:34:27,191
But if you're wrong, Claire...

428
00:34:27,473 --> 00:34:30,863
I don't want you
getting too close to him.

429
00:34:40,636 --> 00:34:41,989
- Thank you.
- No problem.

430
00:34:42,196 --> 00:34:43,834
Look at him.

431
00:34:44,716 --> 00:34:46,947
- He's a star.
- Hi. Really great.

432
00:34:47,397 --> 00:34:50,390
I just want you guys to meet someone.

433
00:34:51,238 --> 00:34:55,915
This is my brother and partner
Nathaniel Jr. And his...

434
00:34:57,039 --> 00:35:00,112
- Jasmine.
- Hey, there, I'm Neil Schaeger.

435
00:35:00,320 --> 00:35:02,356
- Schaeger and Sons, from Flagstaff.
- Raymond Dooley.

436
00:35:02,560 --> 00:35:04,870
Dooley and Moss Funeral Home,
Reno, Nevada.

437
00:35:05,081 --> 00:35:07,231
Moss couldn't be here. Bladder cancer.

438
00:35:07,761 --> 00:35:09,718
That was a hell of a speech
David made.

439
00:35:09,922 --> 00:35:12,914
Almost made me cry when those
Kroehner bastards got up and left.

440
00:35:13,122 --> 00:35:16,798
Those fuckers have been trying
to buy us out for five goddamn years.

441
00:35:17,003 --> 00:35:19,120
Your father was a good man.

442
00:35:19,564 --> 00:35:20,519
Yes, he was.

443
00:35:20,764 --> 00:35:23,403
Y'all don't mind if we drag your
little brother out with us, do you?

444
00:35:23,605 --> 00:35:26,324
- I really shouldn't.
- Gotta let us buy you a drink at least.

445
00:35:26,525 --> 00:35:28,517
- You're our hero.
- Well, maybe just a quick one.

446
00:35:28,726 --> 00:35:31,035
Quick one, my Aunt Fanny.
We're gonna make a night of it.

447
00:35:31,246 --> 00:35:33,124
Hey, you want to go with?
The more the merrier.

448
00:35:34,127 --> 00:35:38,167
Oh, I don't think so.
We're just gonna lay low tonight.

449
00:35:38,368 --> 00:35:43,363
- Yeah, but you guys have fun.
- Okay, your loss.

450
00:36:02,413 --> 00:36:03,766
Excuse me.

451
00:36:04,893 --> 00:36:07,533
We'd just like to thank you...

452
00:36:08,094 --> 00:36:10,767
...very much.
- He looks so beautiful.

453
00:36:10,974 --> 00:36:12,567
I'm glad you're pleased.

454
00:36:12,775 --> 00:36:14,891
Mike's mom and dad
drove down from Salinas.

455
00:36:15,095 --> 00:36:19,772
Yeah. They never got
a chance to meet him.

456
00:36:19,976 --> 00:36:23,572
Now it's almost like they did.

457
00:36:24,497 --> 00:36:29,094
- Do you have children?
- Yes. Yes, I do.

458
00:36:29,298 --> 00:36:35,057
I have a 4-year-old boy and my...

459
00:36:35,260 --> 00:36:36,613
Yes.

460
00:36:40,541 --> 00:36:44,933
We'd like to be alone with him
for a little while, if that's okay.

461
00:36:45,142 --> 00:36:48,373
Oh, absolutely, absolutely.
Please take as much time as you need.

462
00:36:49,182 --> 00:36:51,299
Thanks.

463
00:37:13,948 --> 00:37:16,621
- Say fromage!
- Fromage.

464
00:37:18,469 --> 00:37:22,303
Hey, you were really
great today, Nate.

465
00:37:22,509 --> 00:37:25,582
Standing up to Billy.
I felt like some white-trash girl...

466
00:37:25,790 --> 00:37:28,669
...whose boyfriend
was the biggest badass in town.

467
00:37:28,871 --> 00:37:32,068
- Your brother's seriously ill, Brenda.
- Yeah, whatever.

468
00:37:32,272 --> 00:37:36,743
But you know what?
We're in faux Paris, so let's party.

469
00:39:13,653 --> 00:39:15,006
Hi.

470
00:39:15,613 --> 00:39:18,686
